# 1. Core Architecture:
To understand how Java achieves platform independence and handles memory, you need to understand its three core components:
  #JDK (Java Development Kit): The full software development environment.
  It contains the compiler , tools, and the JRE. You need this to write and compile Java code.
  #JRE (Java Runtime Environment): The software package that provides the class libraries and resources that a Java program
  needs to run.
  #JVM (Java Virtual Machine): The engine that actually executes the bytecode.The JVM is platform-dependent,
  (different for Windows, Mac, Linux), but it reads the same platform-independent bytecode.
# Control statements in java:
  Control statements in Java are instructions that control the order in which code runs. Normally, Java reads code from top to bottom,
  line by line. Control statements break this straight path. They let your program make decisions, repeat code, or skip sections.
#Decision-Making Statements:
  if Statement: Runs a block of code only if the condition is true. If it is false, Java skips it.
  if-else Statement: Gives you two paths. It runs one block if the condition is true, and a different block if it is false.
  else-if Ladder: Used to check many conditions one after another. It runs the block for the first true condition and ignores the rest.
  Nested if: This is an if statement placed inside another if statement. The inner one only runs if the outer one is true.
  switch Statement: Best for testing a single variable against a list of exact values. It is cleaner than using many if-else blocks.
# Looping Statements:
  for Loop: Best used when you know exactly how many times you want to repeat the code. It puts the setup, the condition, and the 
  step counter all in one line.
  while Loop: Checks the condition before running the code. Use this when you do not know the exact number of repeats in advance.
  do-while Loop: Runs the code block first, and then checks the condition. This means the code will always run at least once, 
  even if the condition is false right away.
# Jump Statements:
  break: Instantly stops and exits a loop or a switch block.
  continue: Skips the rest of the current loop cycle and jumps straight to the next turn.
  return: Exits the current method completely and can send a value back.
# Operators:
 Arithmetic Operators:
  + (Addition): Adds two values together.
  - (Subtraction): Subtracts one value from another.
  * (Multiplication): Multiplies two values.
  / (Division): Divides one value by another.
  % (Modulus): Divides two numbers and gives you the remainder left over.
# . Unary Operators:
  ++ (Increment): Increases a value by 1.
  -- (Decrement): Decreases a value by 1.
  + (Positive): Indicates a positive value.
  - (Negative): Turns a positive value into a negative value.
  ! (Logical NOT): Flips a true value to false, or a false value to true.
#  Assignment Operators:
   += , -=, *=, /=: Short ways to do math and assign the result at the same time (e.g., x += 5 is the same as x = x + 5).
# Relational Operators:
  == (Equal to): Checks if two values are the same.
  != (Not equal to): Checks if two values are different.
  > (Greater than) and < (Less than)
  >= (Greater than or equal to) and 
  <= (Less than or equal to).
# Logical Operators:
  && (Logical AND): Returns true only if both conditions are true.
  || (Logical OR): Returns true if at least one condition is true.
# methods in java:
Built-in Methods vs User-Defined Methods:
   Built-in Methods: These are ready-made methods provided by Java. You just use them.
   User-Defined Methods: These are custom methods created by you to do a specific task.


  
  
